    <text id="B0186T">
        <front id="d2">
            <div1 type="summary" id="d3">
                <p>William Staples writes on behalf of a woman who seeks the return of her son,
                    Jack. Her son, only 15 years old, is living in Staunton and is employed without
                    her permission. Staples' letter indicates that the woman seems to have trouble
                    controlling her children, as the father is dead.</p>
            </div1>
        </front>

        <body id="d4">
            <div1 type="letter" id="d5">
                

                <opener>
                    <dateline>
                        <date value="1867-05-13">May 13, <abbr expan="1867">67</abbr></date>
                        <name type="place">Near Amherst <abbr expan="Court House">Co Ho</abbr>
                            <abbr expan="Virginia">Va</abbr></name>
                    </dateline>
                    <salute><abbr expan="Dear">Dr</abbr> Sir-</salute>
                </opener>

                <p>A colored woman named Izetta (formerly belonged to Mays near here) is living on
                    my Farm and requests me to write to the authorities at Staunton and get them to
                    make her son Jack aged 15 years and who has been at Staunton for two or 3 years
                    come home to her at once and to collect his hire and remit it to her to my care
                    person, had no right to employ him -- without her permission said <orig
                        reg="boy's">Boys</orig> Father is not living She seems not to be able to
                    control her Boys of whom she has several</p>

                <closer>
                    <salute><abbr expan="Your">Yr</abbr>
                        <abbr expan="obedient">obt</abbr> servant</salute>
                    <signed><abbr expan="William">Wm</abbr> A Staples</signed>
                </closer>
            </div1>
        </body>
    </text>
